  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has several laws against money laundering. Here are some of the key ones:\n\n*   **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA):** This act requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on certain financial transactions, like large currency transactions, that might indicate money laundering, tax evasion, or other criminal activity. It also requires them to establish anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act made money laundering a federal crime. It prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions with the proceeds of specified unlawful activities.\n\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Passed in response to the September 11th attacks, this act expanded the BSA and other anti-money laundering laws. It includes provisions to strengthen customer identification procedures, increase information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement, and target foreign financial institutions that launder money.\n\nThese laws, along with others, form the framework for combating money laundering in the United States. They impose obligations on financial institutions and other businesses, and they provide law enforcement with tools to investigate and prosecute money laundering offenses.",
